===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|dreem|lang=enm}}, possibly from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|dream|drēam|joy, pleasure, gladness, delight, mirth, rejoicing, rapture, ecstasy, frenzy, music, musical instrument, harmony, melody, song, singing, jubilation, sound of music|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|draumaz|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|draugmaz||festivity, dream, ghost, hallucination, delusion, deception|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|draugaz||delusion, mirage, illusion|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|dʰrAugʰ-|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|dʰreugʰ-||to deceive, injure, damage|lang=ine-pro}}; meaning influenced in Middle English by Old Norse {{term|draumr||lang=non|dream|}}, from same Proto-Germanic root. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|dreme||dream|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|drom||dream|lang=frr}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|dream||dream|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|droom||dream|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Traum||dream|lang=de}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|dröm||dream|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|draumur||dream|lang=is}}. Related also to {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|dreag|drēag|spectre, apparition|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} be{{term|bedrog|drog|deception, deceit|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Trug||deception, illusion|lang=de}}.

The derivation from Old English ''drēam'' is controversial, since the word itself is only attested in writing in its meaning of “joy, mirth, musical sound”. Possibly there was a separate word ''drēam'' meaning “images seen while sleeping”, which was avoided in literature due to potential confusion with “joy” sense, which would account for the common definition in the other Germanic languages, or the derivation may indeed simply be a strange progression from “mirth, joy, musical sound”.<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}.</ref>

Attested words for “sleeping vision” in Old English were {{term|mæting|mǣting|lang=ang}} (Middle English {{term|mæte|lang=enm}}, {{term|mete|mēte|lang=enm}}), from unclear source, and {{term|swefn|lang=ang}} (Modern English {{term|sweven|lang=en}}), from Proto-Germanic {{recons|swefnan|lang=gem-pro}}, from Proto-Indo-European {{recons|swepno-|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|swep-|lang=ine-pro}}; compare {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|ὕπνος||sleep|tr=hypnos|lang=grc}}.

